rComments: Professor Gillman is so adorable. She's clearly passionate about what she teaches and it makes it interesting for the students. Reading are pretty cool, she showed a couple films and narrated them as they were playing it was so obnoxious. She's adorable so you can't even be mad. Grade was based on essays and a final pretty simple.
Go to her office hours. Even if you just skim the reading and go to her office hours you will be fine.

I accidently took this class but it turned out to be very interesting.  Susan is very passionate about the subject and really wants to help. She does tend to go off on rants, but she's not hard to follow. There were three papers each worth 30%. and 10% for attendance.

Susan Gillman is honestly interested in her subject and is always willing to help the students, but her lectures are long and she tends to ramble. She starts talking ten minutes before class begins and doesn't stop until ten minutes after you're supposed to leave. She's a nice person, but her lectures need work.

Susan is very enthusiastic but her lectures are dull. Honestly I learned more on my own or in sections. I very rarely put anything from her lectures into my essays, and that's pretty much all we're graded on. Easy peasy class.

My favorite professor so far. I accidentally took an upper div lit class without knowing, since I'm not a lit major I thought it would be really hard to get a decent grade but I did just fine. She makes you work for your grade, but once you get her style of writing down,it is easier to get a good grade.

I think Susan is a great, friendly, and caring professor who wants her students to succeed.She tends to go off on tangents quite frequently, so try to pay close attention. But the material for this class was very interesting and enjoyable, you see a whole other side of the U.S. I recommend this class to all lit students.

Gillman is definitely my favorite professor so far. Her lectures do ramble a bit, but if you're paying attention in lecture it's not difficult to understand. Her energy is amazing, and when I would ask for essay help, her responses were always extensive and very helpful. I highly recommend taking her class.

Highly recommended!  Susan is extremely nice, and is probably one of the most helpful teachers I have had.  Her lectures were required, and I recommend not ditching them because she prepares you perfectly for both essays and exams during lecture.  Her energy is great, even though she may ramble at times.

Susan is by far my favorite teacher/professor I have ever had. She lectures in a way that invokes different ways of thinking and different ways of interpreting literature. She does ramble at times, but always in a way that will enhance your knowledge of the subject at hand. If you keep up with the readings, this is an easy and enjoyable class.

Susan is a VERY nice woman, but cannot lecture for her life. She rambles, goes back and forth, to the point where you're more confused about the book than ever. I think I will get a good grade in this class, but I don't exactly look forward to it. The reading list is very good though.

Really, really disjointed, rambling lectures that generally detracted from my understanding of the book.  Always lectures a good 5-15mins past the end of class, which is pretty aggravating.  Very nice in office hours, though.  Wouldn't take another class with her...

Susan is very good at pretty much writing your essays for you. she tends to ramble and go past the time limit, but overall she is very good at explaining the texts with ample examples. she is a very kind person too. the class has a TON of reading though but i still pulled off an A. very easy class if you have the right TA

Um, can someone please tell me what the hell this woman is talking about? She rambles on and on and never gets anywhere.  Lectures are totally pointless, and every word that comes out of her mouth makes you more confused.  Easy class, crappy professor.

She means well, but her lectures literally put everyone to sleep. She rants on and on and on in a confusing and otherwise redundant manner. She interrupts not only herseld, but students who try to speak. I don't know anyone else who says "G'HEAD" more than Susan Gillman does.

Professor Gillman's lectures were always completely boring, useless. I have a very strong grasp on how to interpret literature and she was usually blithering about insignificant minute details and not concentrating on important literary readings like themes and metaphors--she'd just concentrate on, say, diction. Also, the reading was terrible.

She may be passionate about her subjects (slavery, slavery, more slavery), but does an inadequate job of laying out to students new to lit interpretation on the process of HOW TO ACTUALLY READ (i.e. understanding subtexts, catching repitions/images/metphors, narrative structure, etc). And her reading list was rather dull (slave narratives, bleh)

Susan is an amazing professor.  She's enthusiastic and makes the early hour more tolerable, plus is extremely supportive of students and loves seeing them in office hours.  Her lectures can be a little confusing if you're trying to memorize them - which you don't need to - but overall very approachable and helpful. I hope she'll be my grad advisor.

this class was WAY demanding but i have to say, i liked it a lot. i now read more books and articles paying closer attention to details. this class rocks. =) who knew lewis carroll was a child ****or =P
Mmmmm mmmmm disorganization.

Professor Gillman had so much energy and excitement for teaching that I wanted to come to class. Her lectures were a little bit disjointed, but the materials she chose for the class were good and she was always willing to let you re-write papers if you got a bad grade. Awesome professor!

Gets really excited about teaching, even at 8:00 AM. Tends to jump around from topic to topic, and always runs out of time before she says everything that she wants to. At least she is really interesting and likes what she does. She goes out of her way to make the class a good experience for all.

What can i say.  I knew LIT 1 would suck.  She didnt seem to be able to focus one one idea enough to establish any clarity.  I would, however, take her in an upper division class where there was a more focused topic.
Her lectures are all over the place!  She is super disorganized and her lectures jump from one idea to another and go in circles.  She has great ideas, but she is very unclear and hard to follow.

her lecturing style is very disjointed and discontinuous, she jumps around a lot.  it was disappointing because she is so excited about teaching and the material and has a lot of really fantastic ideas and insights into the texts.
The best lit professor I have had in my 3 year college career.  She is brilliant and very engaging, which makes her lectures very much the same way.  A must take for any lit major!
Susan is an encouraging and engaging professor.  Pedagogues like her are the reason the University system was founded.
Her classes are always worth it!
